    "content": "Ethiopian federal police have arrested 17 individuals accused of running a human trafficking network that resulted in the deaths of more than 60 migrants and the sexual assault of several women, according to officials. The arrests were announced on Wednesday, highlighting ongoing efforts to curb smuggling along key migration corridors in the Horn of Africa.\n\nThe network, allegedly led by Mohammed Tahir Aden, also known as Werdi, is believed to have smuggled hundreds of migrants through Djibouti and into Yemen, ultimately aiming for Saudi Arabia. Investigators say the group exploited vulnerable people seeking better economic opportunities abroad, often subjecting them to dangerous conditions and abuse.\n\nThe Horn of Africa route is notoriously perilous, with migrants facing risks including dehydration, violence, and drowning. Organized syndicates frequently prey on desperate individuals, charging large sums for passage that often ends in tragedy. The deaths of over 60 people attributed to this network underscore the severe humanitarian toll.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, this arrest is significant because many Somali migrants use similar routes to reach the Gulf states. Families in the diaspora often fund relatives' journeys, only to face losses or trauma. This operation signals potential progress in disrupting the criminal networks that endanger their loved ones.\n\nAuthorities have not disclosed whether the suspects will face charges in Ethiopia or be extradited, but the case is expected to highlight the need for cross-border cooperation to combat smuggling. The investigation continues.\n\nRead the original report from Radio Dalsan here: https://radiodalsan.com/2026/07/23/ethiopian-police-arrest-17-suspects-over-human-smuggling/?utm_source=rss&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=ethiopian-police-arrest-17-suspects-over-human-smuggling",
