    "content": "Ethiopian opposition parties have criticized Prime Minister Abiy Ahmed’s government, alleging that its current approach is pushing the Tigray region toward renewed armed conflict. The accusations follow a fragile peace deal signed in November 2022 that ended a brutal two-year war, but implementation has been slow and contentious.\n\nThe Pretoria Agreement, which halted large-scale fighting, has faced challenges including the disarmament of Tigrayan forces, the return of displaced civilians, and the restoration of essential services. Opposition figures claim that federal authorities are failing to uphold key provisions, instead engaging in actions that exacerbate tensions in the northern region.\n\nRegional security analysts note that any resurgence of violence in Tigray would destabilize the broader Horn of Africa. Neighboring countries like Sudan grapple with internal strife, while parts of Somalia continue to experience insecurity, placing additional strain on already limited peacekeeping and diplomatic resources.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, stability in Ethiopia is crucial. Many Somalis live and work in Ethiopia, and cross-border trade between Somali regions and Ethiopia is vital. Renewed conflict could disrupt livelihoods, cause displacement, and divert attention from counterterrorism efforts in Somalia.\n\nThe international community has urged all parties to fully implement the peace agreement, but progress remains uncertain. Without tangible steps, the risk of a return to arms looms large over the region.\n\nRead the original report from Horseed Media here: https://horseedmedia.net/ethiopia-opposition-accuses-abiy-government-of-steering-tigray-toward-renewed-conflict/424030/",
